<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-03-01T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-03-01T17:00:00-05:00" n="946" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d946">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/2990.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-01T17:00:00-05:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 1, 1912—5 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>A telegram from consul at Chihuahua via El Paso, dated February 29,
                            states Americans at Velardena, besieged since 23d, had a fight with
                            rebels on 27th, driving them off, but that the need of immediate
                            protection or escort to Torreón is imperative.</p>
                        <p>Immediately and most urgently represent to Mexican Government that the
                            needs of Americans at Velardena must be given preference and that an
                            adequate force be sent at once to their relief.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
